(Beginner) Quest 6: Hello World Project
Introduction
In this quest, we’ll be embarking on the first of three projects in this campaign - a Hello World project! You’ll be writing and deploying a simple Solidity smart contract as well as learning other important concepts such as creating a MetaMask wallet, getting Testnet tokens and using a block explorer!
For queries on this quest, join our Discord, head to the #avalanche-helpdesk channel and look for this quest's post.

Learning Outcomes
By the end of this quest, you will be able to: 
  • Describe what smart contracts and decentralized applications are
  • Understand basic concepts of Solidity
  • Set up a MetaMask wallet
  • Deploy a smart contract to the Testnet
  • Use a block explorer to inspect transactions on the blockchain
Deliverable
This quest has one deliverable.
  1. A screenshot of your deployed contract's details on the SnowTrace block explorer. Follow instructions in Step 11 for more details.

Quest Walkthrough
Step 1: Introduction to Smart Contracts
The term Smart Contract (SC) is one that you’ll come across a lot in the blockchain world but what really is a SC and what is it used for? SCs are simply programs stored on the blockchain that are governed by code; this is in contrast to traditional contracts that are governed by people. 
SCs run when certain predetermined conditions are met, all without the need for an intermediary. They allow trusted transactions to be carried out among anonymous parties without the need for a central authority and are used to automate processes on a blockchain. 

Let’s read the article below to find out more about SCs.

Article: IBM - What are Smart Contracts?

Learning Checklist
  • SCs are programs that can automate workflows on a blockchain, triggering actions when specific conditions are met.
  • SCs are fast, efficient and accurate.
  • SCs are secure because of its underlying blockchain technology. Note that improper implementation of SCs can lead to vulnerabilities within the SC that may cause it to be susceptible to attacks.
Step 2: Introduction to Decentralized Applications
Besides SCs, another term you’ll come across frequently is dApps, which stands for Decentralized Applications. These are basically applications that run on a decentralised computing system like a blockchain rather than a centralised server. 
dApps allow you to leverage all the benefits of blockchain and apply them to traditional sectors, providing more open and decentralised alternatives to creative, banking and gaming industries. Check out the article below to get an introduction to dApps - it covers the pros and cons of dApps, and how they compare to traditional centralised applications.

Article: What are dApps?

Learning Checklist
  • dApps are applications that run on a decentralised computing system like a blockchain rather than a centralised server.
  • Compared to centralised applications, dApps are less prone to censorship and generally more secure against attackers.
  • dApps use SCs to execute operations on the blockchain.

Some examples of dApps on Avalanche include Trader Joe, Pangolin Exchange and Benqi, alongside many others!
Step 3: Creating a MetaMask Wallet
Before we proceed with writing our first SC, let’s first create our own MetaMask wallet. If you’re not familiar with the concept of crypto wallets, refer to this article for more information. Essentially, crypto wallets allow you to store your private key on a blockchain and it is this private key that grants you access to your cryptocurrencies and allows you to sign transactions on the blockchain to interact with SCs and dApps.
In this quest, we’ll be introducing a widely used crypto wallet - MetaMask. This crypto wallet serves as a gateway for users to connect to dApps where they can buy, store, send and swap tokens. If you already have a MetaMask wallet set up, you can skip this step.

  1. Head to the MetaMask download tab and click on the ‘Install MetaMask for browser’ button. The message will vary depending on the browser you’re using
  2. You’ll be redirected to your browser’s webstore, add the extension to your browser
  3. Afterwards, a new tab will pop up showing a welcome message. Click on ‘Get started’ followed by ‘Create a wallet’
  4. You’ll be prompted to create a password - this password is required to further secure your account so that if someone gets access to your computer, they won’t immediately get access to your wallet
  5. After that, you will be redirected to the ‘Secure your wallet’ page, where there will be a short video explaining to you the importance of your Secret Recovery Phrase. Watch this video carefully as the information covered is very important
  6. On the next page, click on the ‘Click here to reveal secret words’, take down the recovery phrase and store it in a safe place, do not lose it or tell anyone! This combination of words is essentially your private keys
  7. Next, you will need to confirm the Secret Recovery Phrase that you have copied previously. Select the key phrases in the right order in order to proceed
  8. If you entered it correctly, you will now be at the homepage of the MetaMask wallet and you will able to see something similar to that of the image in ‘Expected output’



For easier access to your MetaMask wallet, you can pin MetaMask extension onto your browser. The MetaMask wallet icon will now appear on the top right-hand corner of your screen. ﻿

Step 4: Connecting to Avalanche Fuji Testnet

If you look at the top right-hand corner of your MetaMask wallet, you’ll see that it is currently connected to the Ethereum Mainnet (boxed in red in the image above). This is the default network that MetaMask connects to when it is first created. However, we’ll be connecting it to the Avalanche Fuji TestNet instead as this is the network where we’ll be deploying our SC to later on.

To do this, click on ‘Ethereum Mainnet’ to open the dropdown list. Then, click on ‘Add network’. After doing so, you’ll be directed to the network setting page. Click on 'Add a network manually' and fill in the details as shown below. 
  • Network name: Avalanche FUJI C-Chain
  • New RPC URL: https://api.avax-test.network/ext/bc/C/rpc
  • Chain ID: 43113
  • Currency symbol: AVAX
  • Block explorer URL (Optional): https://testnet.snowtrace.io/

After you’re done filling up the details, click on ‘Save’. After doing so, you should get an output similar to the image in ‘Expected output’. You have now successfully connected to Avalanche Fuji Testnet!

Step 5: Introduction to Remix IDE
Now that you have created your MetaMask wallet and are connected to Avalanche Fuji Testnet, it's time to write your first SC! In this quest, you will be writing a very simple HelloWorld SC on the Remix Integrated development environment (IDE).   
You might be wondering, what’s an IDE? An IDE is basically a software used to build applications using common developer tools in a graphical user interface. An IDE would normally consist of a source code editor which is similar to a text editor but has features like syntax highlighting and programming language specific auto complete features. An IDE also usually consists of a debugger for testing programs as well as a local build compiler to build and package code needed before running it. 
 
As stated earlier we will be using the Remix IDE to write a smart contract. Remix is a very popular open-source IDE used for writing, compiling and debugging Solidity code. Remix IDE comes in 2 platforms - the Remix Online IDE as well as the Remix Desktop IDE. In this step, we will be using the Remix Online IDE. 
 
First head over to the Remix Online IDE.



The Remix IDE layout can be split into four main parts:
  • Icon Panel - Toggle between different plugins here, the Side Panel will change according to the plugin selected
  • Side Panel - The GUI corresponding to the plugin selected
  • Main Panel - This is where you’ll be writing smart contracts
  • Terminal - View results of the interactions with the plugins here
Step 6: Writing the SC
Alright, time to start writing our SC! First, go to the file explorer in the Side Panel section (refer to the image in Step 5), create a new Solidity file by clicking on the first icon on the left, below “default_workspace”. Name the new file HelloWorld.sol. 
Next in the code editor, add in the following code below. Save the file by pressing “Ctrl” + “S” on your keyboard. 

// SPDX-License-Identifier: MIT  pragma solidity 0.8.18;  contract HelloWorld {  function sayHelloWorld() public pure returns (string memory) {     return "Hello World";  }  }

And we’re done with our HelloWorld SC! Now let’s go through it line by line to make sure that you know what’s happening in this script. 

The first line states that the SC uses the MIT license. This is not important information to focus on if you’re just starting out on your Solidity journey. You can refer here for more information if you’re curious to find out more.

The second line defines the Solidity version that you intend to write this SC in - here we’re using the version 0.8.18.

The third line is how we define contracts in Solidity. We use the contract keyword and give our contract the name of HelloWorld. This is followed with curly brackets { } to demarcate the start and end of the contract.

Inside the contract, we define a function using the keyword function and give the function the name of sayHelloWorld. The function does not have any input parameters, hence the empty (). 

We give the function the public visibility and pure modifier. Don’t stress too much about function visibility and modifiers for now, we’ll cover it in later quests. But if you’re interested now, more information can be found here.

We state that the function returns us a string when it is called. In our function, we see that the exact string that is returned is “Hello World”. memory refers to the memory location allocated, but again, don’t worry about this for now.

Note that since mastering Solidity is outside the scope of this campaign, we’ll only be covering the essential Solidity concepts required for you to understand the SCs covered in the campaign. If you’re interested in learning more about Solidity, you can head to our Introduction to Blockchain & Solidity Learn module!
Step 7: Compiling the SC
Now the next step is to compile the SC! To do this, click on the Compiler icon to open the tab. Then, make sure to change the compiler version to 0.8.18 and click on “Compile HelloWorld.sol” afterwards.
If you’re not familiar with the concept of compiling, it is essentially a process that converts human-readable language into machine-readable language. 

After you’ve done so, you should see a green tick on the Compiler icon, similar to the image in ‘Expected output' below.

You have successfully written and compiled your first SC using Remix IDE!
Expected output
Step 8: Getting AVAX Testnet Tokens
Before we can deploy our newly written SC to the Fuji Testnet, we first need to get some Testnet tokens. This is because transactions on a blockchain incur some form of costs in the form of gas fees. So we’ll need to fund our MetaMask wallet with some Testnet tokens - we can do so using a Testnet faucet!
A Testnet faucet is a dispenser in which developers can request for tokens to be used on the Testnet. When a wallet is newly created, there will not be any AVAX available in the wallet. Hence we’ll need to head to the faucet to get some tokens in our wallet.

  1. First, head over to the AVAX faucet
  2. Open your MetaMask wallet extension to copy your wallet address. You can hover over your wallet address under “Account 1” and click it to copy it to your clipboard
  3. Now in the AVAX faucet website, paste your wallet address into the blank field. Ensure that “Fuji (C-Chain)” is selected for the network field and “AVAX” is selected for the token field. Click on the “REQUEST 2 AVAX” button
  4. Open your MetaMask wallet extension again. If you’re still connected to the “Avalanche FUJI C-Chain” network, you should see that you now have 2 AVAX Testnet tokens in your wallet
  5. Refer to the image in ‘Expected output’ if you are unsure

Troubleshooting: if you have already submitted a request to the faucet in the past 24 hours and intend to make another request, you’ll notice that you’ll be faced with a 24 hour cooldown. Please try to identify the wallet that contains the previously located testnet tokens and transfer your tokens from that wallet instead. 

However, if you have lost access to that wallet and are still facing the cooldown blocker, you can request for Fuji AVAX testnet tokens from Avalanche’s Developer Relations team in their Discord server’s developers-chat. Note that this should not be your first option - be prudent with your testnet tokens.

Awesome! Now our wallet is loaded with Testnet AVAX tokens.
Expected output
Step 9: Deploy Hello World SC to Avax Fuji TestNet using Remix
Now that we have Testnet tokens in our MetaMask wallet, we’re ready to deploy our SC to the Avax Fuji Testnet using Remix IDE. 
Head back to Remix. Click on the Deploy and Run icon. 

Under the “ENVIRONMENT” dropdown list, you’ll see that there are a number of environments to choose from - we’ll be using Injected Provider - Metamask to deploy our SC. Select this option. After doing so, a pop-up will appear on your screen prompt you to connect your MetaMask extension to Remix, click on “Next” and “Connect”.



If you’ve successfully connected your MetaMask extension with Remix, you should see your wallet address as well as your AVAX balance being shown under “ACCOUNT”, similar to the image above.

Now, click on the ‘Deploy’ button. A MetaMask pop-up will appear showing the fees needed to deploy your SC to the AVAX Fuji Testnet. Click ‘Confirm’. Note: if a pop-up does not appear automatically, you might need to manually open MetaMask extension by clicking on the logo on the top-right corner of your browser.

Now go back to your MetaMask wallet, the transaction should show up in the ‘Activity’ tab. Refer to the image in ‘Expected output’ if you require a reference.

You have now successfully deployed your SC to the Avalanche Fuji Testnet. Cool stuff!
Expected output
Step 10: Inspecting Your SC on SnowTrace
In the previous step, we deployed our SC to the Testnet. Now we will be using a block explorer to inspect the transaction. 
But first, what are block explorers? A block explorer is like a visualization layer for a blockchain that acts as a “search engine” of a blockchain. You can use block explorers to inspect transaction issues, assets created on blockchains, and even track transactions as they move from wallet to wallet. Since block explorers are key infrastructures to any blockchain ecosystem, every decent blockchain has at least one block explorer and Avalanche is definitely no exception.

The block explorer that we’ll be using is SnowTrace, which is an Avalanche C-Chain block explorer used to inspect transactions where SCs are involved.

First, go to your MetaMask wallet and click on ‘Contract deployment’ under the ‘Activity’ tab and click on ‘View on block explorer’. 
 
Recall that earlier on when we were adding the Avalanche Fuji Testnet as a new network to our MetaMask wallet, we configured SnowTrace to be our default block explorer. As a result, just by clicking on ‘View on block explorer’, MetaMask redirects us to SnowTrace, and in particular, the page that contains the transaction details of our SC deployment. 



On this page, you can find information regarding the SC deployment such as the block number where the transaction occurred, the address of the wallet that deployed the SC, and the address of the deployed SC alongside other relevant information.



If you click on the address in the ‘To’ section, you’ll be redirected to the page where you can find all the information regarding your SC. This includes how much AVAX is stored in the SC, information regarding the transactions that have interacted with the SC, Bytecode and Opcodes of the SC etc. Important: You will need to know how to access this contract page for your submission.﻿
